## 🐛 Bug Report
When using the Workbook.addImage function in ExcelJS, setting the editAs property to 'oneCell', 'absolute', or leaving it undefined does not produce the expected behavior in Microsoft Excel or LibreOffice. The images do not move or resize with the cells as intended. However, the desired behavior is observed when opening the file in Google Sheets. The goal is to have the image "placed in cell" or "Move and Size with cells".

Lib version: 4.4.0

## Steps To Reproduce
1. Create a new workbook and add a worksheet.​[github.com](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/issues/2096)
2. Add an image to the workbook.​
3. Insert the image into the worksheet using the `addImage` function with the `editAs` property set to `oneCell`, `absolute`, or `undefined`.​
4. Save and open the workbook in Microsoft Excel or LibreOffice.


```javascript
const ExcelJS = require('exceljs');
const workbook = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet('Sheet1');

// Add your image to the workbook
const imageId = workbook.addImage({
  base64: base64,
  extension: 'png',
});

// Define the position and size of the image
worksheet.addImage(imageId, {
  tl: { col: 1, row: 1 }, // Top-left corner
  br: { col: 3, row: 5 }, // Bottom-right corner
  editAs: 'oneCell', // Also tested with 'absolute' and undefined
});

// Save the workbook
await workbook.xlsx.writeFile('output.xlsx');
```

## The expected behaviour:

The image should move and resize with the cells when the editAs property is set to `oneCell` or `undefined`. 
In Microsoft Excel and LibreOffice, the image does not move or resize with the cells as expected. The behavior is inconsistent with the settings of the editAs property. However, in Google Sheets, the image behaves as intended.

​Additional Context:​
 This issue seems to be related to previously reported problems, such as
[Issue #2196](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/issues/2196) and [Issue #2777](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/issues/2777), where the editAs property did not function as expected.

